title: Associate
description: Mrs. Mesa has been with Booz Allen for ten years in multiple capacities. - Mrs Mesa has recently moved to USARPAC’s Irregular Warfare Analysis Cell as an all-source analyst specializing in South Asia. - Mrs Mesa has three years experience as an Afghanistan-Pakistan Regional Expertise and Training Program Senior Instructor and curriculum developer. She has authored curriculum, and continually updated and developed new curriculum focused on Pakistan and the regional militant groups as the program expanded to specialty courses. Mrs. Mesa has six years’ experience in all-source analysis. - From Jul 2005 to Jul 2009, as all-source analyst in the Central Command Joint Intelligence Center South and Central Asia shop, Mrs. Mesa covered political, military counternarcotics and terrorism issues in Pakistan and the South Asian region. She authored and briefed hundreds of finished intelligence products for command and national level leadership and partner nations in support of command initiatives. She deployed to Afghanistan in support of a specialized CT task force and to Qatar as the sole representative for the South and Central Asia team. After the Nov 2008 terrorist attacks in Mumbai, India, she supported a command crisis cell as one of few subject matter experts on Kashmir. - From Aug 2003 to Jul 2005, Mrs. Mesa served as an analyst in Central Command’s Regional issues shop covering transnational issues throughout the region and specializing in counternarcotics. A recognized subject matter expert throughout the intelligence community, she authored counternarcotics intelligence products and briefings for local and national level consumption, advised on command and national policy and directives for the emerging mission and coordinated with NATO partners on efforts in Afghanistan. Her ability to liaise with numerous offices and partner nation representatives was key to providing advice at the command and national policy level to the counternarcotics mission.

description: Mrs. Mesa has five years experience in program management and Signals Intelligence (SIGINT) as a Naval Cryptologic Officer. - From Oct 2001 to Jan 2003, she served as the Assistant Officer in Charge at the Joint Interagency Task Force-South Cryptologic Service Group, responsible for a 20 person joint service unit conducting cryptologic support for the command’s counternarcotics mission. She advised and supported the Task Force on Cryptologic programs and policy and refined system capabilities to increase ease and speed of support to the command. She was the key liaison between the joint command and national SIGINT authorities, advising on systems and with SIGINT in support of counternarcotics efforts in the southern hemisphere. - From Jan 2000 to Oct 2001, Mrs Mesa served as the Operations Division Officer at Naval Security Group Activity Sabana Seca, Puerto Rico, Mrs Mesa was responsible for a 60 person operational division in support of national Signals Intelligence tasking. She also deployed while at this duty station as the Officer in Charge aboard the USNS STALWART, Mrs Mesa was responsible for a joint military detachment while deployed in the Southern Command area of responsibility in support of counternarcotics operations. She coordinated with national and regional systems offices to increase collection capability by 150% for her mission and launched a new collection platform. - As the Electronic Materiels Officer and Fiscal Officer at the Naval Security Group Department, Guam from Jun 1998 to Dec 1999, Mrs Mesa managed an 80 person maintenance division responsible for the upkeep of over 150 million dollars in satellite communications equipment and was responsible for an eight million dollar departmental budget. She headed up the department closure planning efforts, coordinating and planning for the secure removal of over 200 million dollars of equipment and redistribution to other Security Group assets.

description: Previous active duty Air Force career operational experience includes; serving abroad as a USAF Foreign Area Officer - Western Hemisphere Specialist, having served with the Defense Security Cooperation Agency and diplomatic military liaison service with United States Embassies in Latin, Central and South America (Caribbean Basin, Panama, Colombia, Peru and Ecuador). Other assignments include; serving as Chief, Latin American Affairs in Panama and as a Defense Language Institute Instructor in Puerto Rico (PR). I began my military career by serving with the PR Army National Guard, as a civilian GS-5 English Instructor. I enlisted with the PR Air Guard and transitioned to active duty as a strategic bomber navigator in the early 1980s. I also served several Joint Duty tours as an Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE) deployed USAF liaison resource and special duty P-3 aircrew member. I am a combat war veteran of the Cold War, first Gulf War in Iraq and Kuwait, the Global War on Narco-Terrorism and the Global War on Terror.

Three Deskside briefings given to VADM Wilson, Director, DIA. • While assigned to the OICC, I was required to work with several ADP systems and databases on a daily basis. These systems included: JDISS, JWICS VTC, RFI System - COLISEUM, SAFE, Internet, Intelink, Intelink-S, Intelink-C (Stone Ghost), Stone Fire, and other DIA NT based systems and programs.

title: Team Leader
description: When thinking about successful organizations, everyone knows about the US Navy & Marine Corps FA-18 Flight Demonstration Squadron, the BLUE ANGELS – who have taken on the mantra of being “Ambassadors of Good Will.” Their decades long history (since 1946) of consistantly building upon a solid track-record of amazing successful achievement can be broken down to a four-step process: • BELIEF LEVEL – with vision and clarity they sustain growth in a high level of belief in four areas: their PROCESSES, their PRODUCT(S), their PEOPLE, and their PURPOSE. • BRIEFING – they’ve compiled a detailed PLAN, every part of which contains inherent FOCUS on the end result and is COMMUNICATED succinctly as possible, in clear and understandable terms. • CONTRACTS – every member of their team has a high level of TRUST in the competencies of their fellows, is committed to the flawless EXECUTION of their assigned tasks, and holds a strong sense of COMMITMENT to their mission. • DEBRIEFING – after every “performance” – regardless of it being a rehearsal or one of the over 70 air shows performed before millions of spectators every year – every member of the team, without regard to rank or experience level differences, acknowledges mistakes that they’ve made and clearly states the corrective actions that they will take to eliminate the possibility of repetition of those errors. With each and every subsequent DEBRIEFING – which assesses their strengths and weaknesses, fosters discipline both individually and collectively, and instills a high level of accountability – the BELIEF LEVEL of the team members in themselves and in each other grows ever greater, liberating them to attain increasingly higher levels of competency individually and continually exceed previous expectations together as a team. Members of the BLUE ANGELS are constantly heard saying: "I'm happy to be here." They're all enthusiastically committed to continuous exemplary performance of their assigned tasks.
name: Thomas Johnson

title: Team Leader
description: When thinking about successful organizations, everyone knows about the US Navy & Marine Corps FA-18 Flight Demonstration Squadron, the BLUE ANGELS – who have taken on the mantra of being “Ambassadors of Good Will.” Their decades long history (since 1946) of consistantly building upon a solid track-record of amazing successful achievement can be broken down to a four-step process: • BELIEF LEVEL – with vision and clarity they sustain growth in a high level of belief in four areas: their PROCESSES, their PRODUCT(S), their PEOPLE, and their PURPOSE. • BRIEFING – they’ve compiled a detailed PLAN, every part of which contains inherent FOCUS on the end result and is COMMUNICATED succinctly as possible, in clear and understandable terms. • CONTRACTS – every member of their team has a high level of TRUST in the competencies of their fellows, is committed to the flawless EXECUTION of their assigned tasks, and holds a strong sense of COMMITMENT to their mission. • DEBRIEFING – after every “performance” – regardless of it being a rehearsal or one of the over 70 air shows performed before millions of spectators every year – every member of the team, without regard to rank or experience level differences, acknowledges mistakes that they’ve made and clearly states the corrective actions that they will take to eliminate the possibility of repetition of those errors. With each and every subsequent DEBRIEFING – which assesses their strengths and weaknesses, fosters discipline both individually and collectively, and instills a high level of accountability – the BELIEF LEVEL of the team members in themselves and in each other grows ever greater, liberating them to attain increasingly higher levels of competency individually and continually exceed previous expectations together as a team. Members of the BLUE ANGELS are constantly heard saying: "I'm happy to be here." They're all enthusiastically committed to continuous exemplary performance of their assigned tasks.

title: Team Leader
description: When thinking about successful organizations, everyone knows about the US Navy & Marine Corps FA-18 Flight Demonstration Squadron, the BLUE ANGELS – who have taken on the mantra of being “Ambassadors of Good Will.” Their decades long history (since 1946) of consistantly building upon a solid track-record of amazing successful achievement can be broken down to a four-step process: • BELIEF LEVEL – with vision and clarity they sustain growth in a high level of belief in four areas: their PROCESSES, their PRODUCT(S), their PEOPLE, and their PURPOSE. • BRIEFING – they’ve compiled a detailed PLAN, every part of which contains inherent FOCUS on the end result and is COMMUNICATED succinctly as possible, in clear and understandable terms. • CONTRACTS – every member of their team has a high level of TRUST in the competencies of their fellows, is committed to the flawless EXECUTION of their assigned tasks, and holds a strong sense of COMMITMENT to their mission. • DEBRIEFING – after every “performance” – regardless of it being a rehearsal or one of the over 70 air shows performed before millions of spectators every year – every member of the team, without regard to rank or experience level differences, acknowledges mistakes that they’ve made and clearly states the corrective actions that they will take to eliminate the possibility of repetition of those errors. With each and every subsequent DEBRIEFING – which assesses their strengths and weaknesses, fosters discipline both individually and collectively, and instills a high level of accountability – the BELIEF LEVEL of the team members in themselves and in each other grows ever greater, liberating them to attain increasingly higher levels of competency individually and continually exceed previous expectations together as a team. Members of the BLUE ANGELS are constantly heard saying: "I'm happy to be here." They're all enthusiastically committed to continuous exemplary performance of their assigned tasks.
name: Thomas Johnson
